    <item>
      <title>Operating on search matches using gn</title>
      <description>&amp;lt;p&amp;gt;The &amp;lt;code&amp;gt;gn&amp;lt;/code&amp;gt; command (introduced in Vim 7.4) makes it easy to operate on regions of text that match the current search pattern. It's especially useful when used with a regex that matches text regions of variable length.&amp;lt;/p&amp;gt;

</description>
      <enclosure url="http://media.vimcasts.org/videos/63/gn-command.m4v" length="10070454" type="video/x-m4v"/>
      <pubDate>Tue, 11 Feb 2014 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate>
      <guid>http://vimcasts.org/episodes/operating-on-search-matches-using-gn/</guid>
      <link>http://vimcasts.org/episodes/operating-on-search-matches-using-gn/</link>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Creating mappings that accept a count</title>
      <description>&amp;lt;p&amp;gt;Lots of Vim's built-in Normal mode commands can be executed multiple times by prefixing them with a count. User-defined Normal mode mappings don't usually handle counts the way we might like them to. We'll explore a couple of techniques for making our custom mappings respond predictably to a count.&amp;lt;/p&amp;gt;

</description>
      <enclosure url="http://media.vimcasts.org/videos/62/map-with-count.m4v" length="10336771" type="video/x-m4v"/>
      <pubDate>Thu, 06 Feb 2014 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate>
      <guid>http://vimcasts.org/episodes/creating-mappings-that-accept-a-count/</guid>
      <link>http://vimcasts.org/episodes/creating-mappings-that-accept-a-count/</link>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Follow my leader</title>
      <description>&amp;lt;p&amp;gt;Choosing a key-map for your custom Vim commands can be difficult. The common advice is to use &amp;lt;code&amp;gt;&amp;amp;lt;leader&amp;amp;gt;&amp;lt;/code&amp;gt; for user-defined mappings, but that's not the only option. There are dozens of two-key mappings that are not bound to any built-in functionality. These available mappings are easy to find if you follow a simple formula.&amp;lt;/p&amp;gt;

</description>
      <pubDate>Wed, 05 Feb 2014 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate>
      <guid>http://vimcasts.org/blog/2014/02/follow-my-leader/</guid>
      <link>http://vimcasts.org/blog/2014/02/follow-my-leader/</link>
    </item>
