      <title>The copy/paste series - a retrospective</title>
      <description>&amp;lt;p&amp;gt;Episodes &amp;lt;a href=&amp;quot;/e/51&amp;quot;&amp;gt;51&amp;lt;/a&amp;gt;, &amp;lt;a href=&amp;quot;/e/52&amp;quot;&amp;gt;52&amp;lt;/a&amp;gt;, &amp;lt;a href=&amp;quot;/e/53&amp;quot;&amp;gt;53&amp;lt;/a&amp;gt;, &amp;lt;a href=&amp;quot;/e/54&amp;quot;&amp;gt;54&amp;lt;/a&amp;gt;, &amp;lt;a href=&amp;quot;/e/55&amp;quot;&amp;gt;55&amp;lt;/a&amp;gt;, &amp;lt;a href=&amp;quot;/e/58&amp;quot;&amp;gt;58&amp;lt;/a&amp;gt;, and &amp;lt;a href=&amp;quot;/e/59&amp;quot;&amp;gt;59&amp;lt;/a&amp;gt; are all on the topic of copy and paste in Vim. I think that this is one area where Vim is especially confusing, partly because of &amp;lt;a href=&amp;quot;http://vimcasts.org/episodes/meet-the-yank-register#vim-jargon&amp;quot;&amp;gt;Vim's non-standard jargon for cut, copy and paste operations&amp;lt;/a&amp;gt;. It's not the most intuitive copy/paste system, but it's usable when you get the hang of certain concepts and techniques.&amp;lt;/p&amp;gt;

</description>
      <pubDate>Mon, 18 Nov 2013 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate>
      <guid>http://vimcasts.org/blog/2013/11/the-copypaste-series-a-retrospective/</guid>
