    <item>
      <title>Using Vim's named registers</title>
      <description>&amp;lt;p&amp;gt;We've met Vim's &amp;lt;a href=&amp;quot;http://vimdoc.sourceforge.net/htmldoc/change.html#quotequote&amp;quot;&amp;gt;default register&amp;lt;/a&amp;gt; and the &amp;lt;a href=&amp;quot;http://vimdoc.sourceforge.net/htmldoc/change.html#quote0&amp;quot;&amp;gt;yank register&amp;lt;/a&amp;gt;. This time, we're going to look at the &amp;lt;a href=&amp;quot;http://vimdoc.sourceforge.net/htmldoc/change.html#quote_alpha&amp;quot;&amp;gt;named registers&amp;lt;/a&amp;gt;, which are handy if you want to cut or copy some text that you intend to paste multiple times.&amp;lt;/p&amp;gt;

</description>
      <enclosure url="http://media.vimcasts.org/videos/53/named-registers.m4v" length="9269387" type="video/x-m4v"/>
      <pubDate>Fri, 04 Oct 2013 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate>
      <guid>http://vimcasts.org/episodes/using-vims-named-registers/</guid>
      <link>http://vimcasts.org/episodes/using-vims-named-registers/</link>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Meet the yank register</title>
      <description>&amp;lt;p&amp;gt;Vim's default register is not a safe place to keep yanked text that you want to paste later. It's all too easy to clobber the default register with a &amp;lt;code&amp;gt;d&amp;lt;/code&amp;gt; or &amp;lt;code&amp;gt;x&amp;lt;/code&amp;gt; command. Luckily, the last yanked text is kept safe in Vim's &amp;lt;a href=&amp;quot;http://vimdoc.sourceforge.net/htmldoc/change.html#quote0&amp;quot;&amp;gt;yank register&amp;lt;/a&amp;gt;.&amp;lt;/p&amp;gt;

</description>
      <enclosure url="http://media.vimcasts.org/videos/52/yank-register.m4v" length="9394643" type="video/x-m4v"/>
      <pubDate>Mon, 30 Sep 2013 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate>
      <guid>http://vimcasts.org/episodes/meet-the-yank-register/</guid>
      <link>http://vimcasts.org/episodes/meet-the-yank-register/</link>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Simple operations using the default register</title>
      <description>&amp;lt;p&amp;gt;Vim's &amp;lt;a href=&amp;quot;http://vimdoc.sourceforge.net/htmldoc/change.html#quotequote&amp;quot;&amp;gt;default register&amp;lt;/a&amp;gt; makes it easy to perform some of the most basic types of cut, copy, and paste operations. That's partly thanks to the &amp;lt;a href=&amp;quot;http://vimdoc.sourceforge.net/htmldoc/change.html#p&amp;quot;&amp;gt;&amp;lt;code&amp;gt;p&amp;lt;/code&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/a&amp;gt; command, which behaves differently depending on whether the default register contains a characterwise or linewise region of text.&amp;lt;/p&amp;gt;

</description>
      <enclosure url="http://media.vimcasts.org/videos/51/default-register.m4v" length="9777137" type="video/x-m4v"/>
      <pubDate>Fri, 27 Sep 2013 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate>
      <guid>http://vimcasts.org/episodes/simple-operations-using-the-default-register/</guid>
      <link>http://vimcasts.org/episodes/simple-operations-using-the-default-register/</link>
