    <item>
      <title>Working title: Practical Vim</title>
      <description>&amp;lt;p&amp;gt;I am very pleased to announce that the &amp;lt;a href=&amp;quot;http://pragprog.com/&amp;quot;&amp;gt;Pragmatic Bookshelf&amp;lt;/a&amp;gt; will be publishing my book on Vim. The working title is &amp;lt;em&amp;gt;Practical Vim&amp;lt;/em&amp;gt;, and I hope to complete it by the spring of 2011. Here is a synopsis:&amp;lt;/p&amp;gt;

&amp;lt;blockquote&amp;gt;
  &amp;lt;p&amp;gt;For an open source project Vim’s documentation is impressive in scope, but there is still a considerable barrier between the novice and the productive Vim user. Whereas it is possible to improve as a programmer or writer by reading other people’s code, poetry or prose, there are fewer opportunities to learn how to use an editor effectively. Vim’s documentation reads like a dictionary; I propose to write a phrasebook.&amp;lt;/p&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;/blockquote&amp;gt;

</description>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Nov 2010 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate>
      <guid>http://vimcasts.org/blog/2010/11/working-title-practical-vim/</guid>
      <link>http://vimcasts.org/blog/2010/11/working-title-practical-vim/</link>
